<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-20T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-20T09:00:00-05:00" n="203" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d203">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.114/167</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract]</seg>
                            </opener>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-20T22:00:00+08:00">
                                        <hi rend="italic">July 20, 1918, 10 p.m.</hi>
                                    </date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>Your July 10, 4 p.m. I am requested by the Acting Minister for
                                Foreign Affairs to assure you that the decision of the Chinese
                                Government to purchase the 1,600 chests of opium remaining in the
                                hands of the combine contemplates its use solely for medicinal
                                purposes and that there will be no retrogression from the policy of
                                opium suppression hitherto followed by this Government. In promising
                                to convey this assurance I took occasion to express the regret which
                                our Government would feel if this were not the case. …</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>